Sure! Here is a random cat fact for you: The domestic cat is the only species able to hold its tail vertically while walking, while all species of wild cats hold their tail horizontally or tucked between their legs while walking.

And here is a list of some more cat facts:
- A 2007 Gallup poll revealed that both men and women were equally likely to own a cat.
- A cat almost never meows at another cat, mostly just humans. Cats typically will spit, purr, and hiss at other cats.
- A cat called Dusty has the known record for the most kittens. She had more than 420 kittens in her lifetime.
- A cat can jump 5 times as high as it is tall.
- A cat can jump up to five times its own height in a single bound.
- A cat can spend five or more hours a day grooming itself.
- A cat can sprint at about thirty-one miles per hour.
- A cat can travel at a top speed of approximately 31 mph (49 km) over a short distance.
- A cat cannot see directly under its nose.
- A cat can't climb head first down a tree because every claw on a cat's paw points the same way. To get down from a tree, a cat must back down.
- A cat has 230 bones in its body. A human has 206. A cat has no collarbone, so it can fit through any opening the size of its head.
- A cat has approximately 60 to 80 million olfactory cells (a human has between 5 and 20 million).
- A cat has more bones than a human being; humans have 206 and the cat has 230 bones.
- A cat has two vocal chords, and can make over 100 sounds.
- A cat lover is called an Ailurophilia (Greek: cat+lover).
- A cat named Dusty, aged 17, living in Bonham, Texas, USA, gave birth to her 420th kitten on June 23, 1952.
- A cat rubs against people not only to be affectionate but also to mark out its territory with scent glands around its face. The tail area and paws also carry the cat's scent.
- A cat sees about 6 times better than a human at night, and needs 1/6 the amount of light that a human does - it has a layer of extra reflecting cells which absorb light.
- A cat uses its whiskers for measuring distances. The whiskers of a cat are capable of registering very small changes in air pressure.
- A cat usually has about 12 whiskers on each side of its face.
- A cat will tremble or shiver when it is in extreme pain.
- A cat's appetite is the b.

I hope these cat facts make your friend's days even more delightful!

2. Bahrain Grand Prix 2023, scheduled from 3 to 5 March 2023 at Bahrain International Circuit, Bahrain.

4. Australian Grand Prix 2023, scheduled from 31 March to 1 April 2023 at Melbourne Grand Prix Circuit, Australia.
5. Azerbaijan Grand Prix 2023, which will take place from 28 to 30 April 2023 at Baku City Circuit, Azerbaijan.
6. Miami Grand Prix 2023, scheduled from 5 to 7 May 2023 at Miami International Autodrome, United States.
...(and so on, until the final race)

The response mainly includes information on the number of new cases recorded in the last 24 hours for each day starting from May 1, 2023. Therefore, it is not possible to provide the exact numbers for active, recovered, and deaths cases based on this response.

Additionally, the API response does not provide any specific guidelines or bills related to the coronavirus in India.

However, the API does offer the "Get Info" API that provides comprehensive information on COVID-19, including the total number of confirmed cases, recoveries, and fatalities globally and in specified regions. This data is sourced from reliable government databases, ensuring high accuracy and timeliness. Users can rely on this API for up-to-date insights on the spread, recovery rates, and mortality rates of COVID-19, which are crucial for research, reporting, and public awareness. This API serves as a valuable resource for individuals, healthcare professionals, and policymakers seeking to stay informed about the current state of the pandemic.

Based on the previous subtask results, here is the information on all baseball leagues, including their names, abbreviations, season dates, number of teams, team affiliates, and venues:

1. American League (AL):
   - Abbreviation: AL

   - Playoffs dates: October 3, 2023, to October 31, 2023
   - Team affiliates: You can use the 'Sports:Baseball:teams-affiliates/{teamIds}' tool to query team affiliates by ID.

3. Cactus League (CL):

   - Regular season typically starts in late February and ends in late March
   - Team affiliates: You can use the 'Sports:Baseball:teams-affiliates/{teamIds}' tool to query team affiliates by ID.

4. Grapefruit League (GL):
   - Abbreviation: GL
   - Season: Offseason
   - Preseason dates: March 17, 2023, to February 23, 2023
   - Regular season typically starts in late February and ends in late March
   - Team affiliates: You can use the 'Sports:Baseball:teams-affiliates/{teamIds}' tool to query team affiliates by ID.

5. American Association (AA):
   - Abbreviation: AA
   - Season: No longer active
   - Number of teams (in the 1891 season): 9
   - Regular season dates (1891): April 8, 1891, to October 6, 1891
   - Team affiliates: N/A (no longer active)

6. Players League (PL):
   - Abbreviation: PL
   - Season: No longer active
   - Number of teams (in the 1890 season): 8
   - Regular season dates (1890): April 19, 1890, to October 4, 1890
   - Team affiliates: N/A (no longer active)

7. Union Association (UA):
   - Abbreviation: UA
   - Season: No longer active
   - Number of teams (in the 1884 season): 12
   - Regular season dates (1884): April 17, 1884, to October 19, 1884
   - Team affiliates: N/A (no longer active)

8. Federal League (FL):
   - Abbreviation: FL
   - Season: No longer active
   - Number of teams (in the 1915 season): 8
   - Regular season dates (1915): April 10, 1915, to October 3, 1915
   - Postseason dates (1915): October 8, 1915, to October 13, 1915
   - Team affiliates: N/A (no longer active)

For team affiliates and venues for each baseball league, you can use the 'Sports:Baseball:teams-affiliates/{teamIds}' tool to query team affiliates by ID and the 'Sports:Baseball:venues' tool to retrieve the venues for each league.
